Material.Text: Scattered throughout the upper Mississippi valley are a series of effigy mounds, which are piles of earth that have been built into forms representing animals, humans, and other symbols. The largest of these mounds that remains is the Great Serpent Mound of Ohio, which measures 1,348 feet (411 meters) long and is 3 feet (1 meter) high. These mounds were built by the native peoples living in the region nearly one thousand years ago, but their purpose is still a mystery. Some of the mounds contained tools, pottery, and human remains, suggesting that they were burial sites. Other evidence suggests that some of them may have been used to mark the seasons, and others may have marked the territory between tribes. Whatever their purpose, the mounds are a voice from ancient history that still <u>reverberates</u> in the modern world.

Material.Text: The "gluten-free" movement recommends that people cut gluten, a protein found in grains like wheat, rye, and barley, from their diets. The vast majority of people are able to digest gluten, but for people with celiac disease, the consumption of gluten is genuinely dangerous. For these people, the rise of gluten-free awareness is both a blessing and a curse. On the positive side, because it is in the public consciousness, there are many more food choices available to them. On the negative side, because there are so many people who claim to be gluten intolerant, some people assume that people with celiac disease don't eat gluten just for better health and not because gluten triggers an autoimmune response. In this case, the <u>gravity</u> of the disease isn't taken seriously, and they may get served foods containing gluten anyway.

Material.Text: Microfinance, or financial services provided to the extremely poor, is an emerging tool that is helping to break the cycle of poverty for many. A part of the problem for underprivileged people is that they have no access to financial services and therefore no way to generate or save income. Microfinance is helping to change that. For example, one of the tools of microfinance is the microloan, which is a very small loan (sometimes just a few hundred dollars). People who are given these microloans then have the means to start a small business and use their profits to repay the loan. After repaying the loan, these people have an established business and a source of income for their families. This small boost of income empowers people and is having a positive impact in the world's neediest regions.

Material.Text: Bionic exoskeletons, or "wearable robots," sound like something out of a science-fiction movie. They are real, however, and are now making their way into people's lives. While one might think that the objective of these exoskeletons is to turn us into superheroes, the truth is they are helping certain people to move and walk again. For many bionic exoskeleton designs, the exoskeleton user straps on the machine to his or her legs, back, and arms, and then is able to move thanks to battery-powered motors that move the legs. The machine is noninvasive and uses external sensors to maintain balance and propel the user into motion. This generation of technology is opening a world of possibilities for patients with particular injuries.

Material.Text:
The headlong race to merge has spread to all industrialized countries. In the ten years from 1986 to 1996 mergers went up by 15%, but 1996 was far from the high point. In the first quarter of 1999 alone, more than 2,500 cross-border mergers were signed. The stock market followed in their wake by pushing up the share prices of the companies concerned.
But will all this corporate shopping be good for economies around the globe? Some experts say that mergers are the result of deregulation. Fierce competition has always been a strong incentive to merge. Companies can expect to benefit from economies of scale and boost their market share. Additionally, if there's good synergy between merged corporations, increases in profits can be achieved in all areas.
